│ stop({"edit_points": [[2158, 2201,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.           │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes with an assertion in    │
│ VPTransformState::get(VPValue*, bool) that fires when a client requests a     │
│ single scalar per part (NeedsScalar=true) for a VPValue that already has      │
│ multiple per-lane scalar values cached. The specific assertion verifies that  │
│ when onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) is true, there must be exactly one scalar         │
│ recorded (the first lane) for that Def. The reproducer constructs a           │
│ predicated instruction feeding a phi/select (VPBlend) whose users only        │
│ consume the first lane, but the VPlan execution generates scalars for all     │
│ lanes for the VPPredInstPHIRecipe, violating the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing   │
│ opt's Log:\n- The debug-only=vplan trace shows a replicated, predicated udiv, │
│ with VPPredInstPHIRecipes merging values inside predicated regions:           │
│ pred.udiv.if/pred.udiv.continue blocks. Later, during VPBlendRecipe::execute, │
│ it queries inputs using State.get(..., OnlyFirstLaneUsed) where               │
│ OnlyFirstLaneUsed = vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this) on the VPBlend.\n- The   │
│ crash happens in VPTransformState::get when NeedsScalar=true for a Def that   │
│ is a VPPredInstPHIRecipe (from debugger:                                      │
│ Def->getDefiningRecipe()->getVPDefID() = 26, which maps to                    │
│ VPPredInstPHIRecipe).\n- The assertion condition includes                     │
│ !vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def) || (hasScalarValue(Def, lane0) &&            │
│ Data.VPV2Scalars[Def].size() == 1). We violated this because                  │
│ onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def)==true but multiple lanes were populated for Def.\n\n3. │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\n- VPPredInstPHIRecipe::execute is executed in a         │
│ replicator region with State.Lane set for each lane. It unconditionally       │
│ creates and caches a scalar phi for the current lane (State.set(this, Phi,    │
│ *State.Lane)) when its operand has no vector value. This happens for all      │
│ lanes 0..VF-1. Later, a user (VPBlend) determines only first lane is needed   │
│ (vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this) == true) and calls State.get(...,           │
│ NeedsScalar=true). This requires that the producer’s value be available as a  │
│ single scalar (first lane only). However, because VPPredInstPHIRecipe already │
│ produced scalars for multiple lanes, the assertion fires.\n- Other recipes    │
│ that can produce per-lane values already honor onlyFirstLaneUsed and limit    │
│ generation to the first lane (see VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute and          │
│ VPInstruction::generate paths). VPPredInstPHIRecipe::execute was missing this │
│ guard.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                                  │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp, function                      │
│ VPPredInstPHIRecipe::execute.\n- Add a guard to honor                         │
│ vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this) and skip generating per-lane phis for lanes  │
│ > 0. This ensures that if all users only use the first lane, the recipe       │
│ records exactly one scalar (lane 0), satisfying the assertion in              │
│ VPTransformState::get.\n\nSuggested patch (conceptual):\n\nvoid               │
│ VPPredInstPHIRecipe::execute(VPTransformState &State) {\n  assert(State.Lane  │
│ && \"Predicated instruction PHI works per instance.\");\n  // If only the     │
│ first lane is used by all users, avoid generating per-lane\n  // scalars for  │
│ lanes > 0. This keeps a single scalar per part, as required\n  // by          │
│ VPTransformState::get when NeedsScalar=true.\n  if                            │
│ (vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(this) && !State.Lane->isFirstLane())\n            │
│ return;\n  ... existing code ...\n}\n\n- This change mirrors the approach     │
│ used in other recipes to restrict codegen based on onlyFirstLaneUsed.\n\n5.   │
│ Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by VPPredInstPHIRecipe unconditionally       │
│ generating per-lane scalars even when downstream users demand only the first  │
│ lane. Adding a guard to skip lane>0 generation when onlyFirstLaneUsed(this)   │
